<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Arctostaphylos</i> <i>crustacea</i>, <i>Arctostaphylos</i> <i>regismontana</i> or <i>Arctostaphylos</i> <i>tomentosa</i> is dominant, co-dominant, or characteristically present in the shrub canopy with <i>Adenostoma</i> <i>fasciculatum</i>, <i>Arctostaphylos</i> spp., <i>Artemisia</i> <i>californica</i>, <i>Baccharis</i> <i>pilularis</i>, <i>Ceanothus</i> spp., <i>Cercocarpus</i> <i>montanus</i>, <i>Chrysolepis</i> <i>chrysophylla</i> var. <i>minor</i>, <i>Ericameria</i> <i>ericoides</i>, <i>Eriogonum</i> <i>fasciculatum</i>, <i>Frangula</i> <i>californica</i>, <i>Heteromeles</i> <i>arbutifolia</i>, <i>Salvia</i> <i>mellifera</i> and <i>Toxicodendron</i> <i>diversilobum</i>. Emergent trees may be present at low cover, including <i>Pinus</i> <i>coulteri</i> or <i>Quercus</i> <i>agrifolia</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 3 m; canopy is intermittent to continuous. Herbaceous layer is sparse. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Arctostaphylos crustacea</i> or <i>A. tomentosa</i> > 30% relative cover in the shrub canopy (cf. Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003a).</li>
		
		<li><i>Arctostaphylos</i> spp. > 30% relative cover in the shrub canopy, while  <i>Quercus pacifica </i>or<i> Adenostoma fasciculatum</i> may also be > 30% relative cover (Rodriguez et al. 2017).</li>
		
		<li><i>Arctostaphylos crustacea</i> > 50% relative cover in the shrub canopy, or > 30% relative cover with <i>Adenostoma fasciculatum, Arctostaphylos regismontana, Frangula californica, Quercus parvula</i>, or <i>Q. wislizeni</i> var. <i>frutescens</i> (Sikes et al. 2021).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Uplands near the coast or within maritime climatic influence including bluffs, dunes, mesas, outcrops, slopes, terraces. Soils are derived from many substrates and usually nutrient-poor sandstone, shale, sand deposits, and granitics.  </div>
</div>

        
