<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Arctostaphylos crustacea </i>is a long-lived, erect, spreading manzanita with a well-developed lignotuber, smooth to exfoliating stem bark, and bi-facial leaves (Parker et al. 2007, 2012). <i>A crustacea </i>is a highly variable species, previously treated as part of <i>A. tomentosa </i>in <i>The Jepson Manual</i>. We follow the Parker et al. treatment of <i>A. crustacea, </i>which includes six subspecies. The more typical ssp <i>. crustacea </i>characterizes the alliance along the central coast from Napa and San Francisco to Santa Barbara Cos., and ssp. <i>crinita </i>occurs as stands in the Santa Cruz Mountains. Ssp. <i>rosei </i>occurs uncommonly from San Francisco to Monterey Co., though past herbarium records provide Santa Barbara Co. as its furthest south locale. Ssp. <i>eastwoodiana </i>(a CNPS list 1B.1 plant) has five occurrences in Santa Barbara Co., and ssp. <i>insulicola </i>and ssp. <i>subcordata </i>(CNPS list 4 plants) occur in the Channel Islands. Stands of this species have edaphic restrictions to coarse marine sandstone, aeolian sand deposits, shale, granitics, and fine textured mud and siltstones (Keeler- Wolf et al. 2003a, Sawyer and Evens 2007, UCB 2005). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Arctostaphylos tomentosa </i>is a long-lived manzanita with a well-developed lignotuber, persistently shredding stem bark, and bi-facial leaves. <i>A. tomentosa </i>includes four subspecies per Parker et al. (2007, 2012); ssp. <i>tomentosa </i>is the most common, occurring primarily in Monterey and San Luis Obispo Cos., though it appears to range as far north and south as Santa Cruz and Santa Barbara Cos., including Santa Cruz Island. The other subspecies, ssp. <i>bracteosa </i>and ssp. <i>hebeclada, </i>are uncommon on shale in Monterey Co., and they may range as far north as San Francisco Co.; ssp. <i>daciticola </i>(a rare CNPS list 1B plant) is endemic to dacite soils in central San Luis Obispo Co. <br/>
<br/>
The alliance includes stands where <i>A. c. </i>ssp. <i>crustacea, </i>ssp. <i>crinita, </i>and ssp. <i>rosei </i>are dominant or codominant in the shrub canopy; ssp. <i>eastwoodiana </i>grows in the <i>Arctostaphylos </i>( <i>purissima, rudis</i>) special stands at Burton Mesa in Santa Barbara Co. The other subspecies of <i>A. crustacea </i>are part of the island chaparral (see the discussion in the Changes Since the First Edition section). Some stands in the East Bay Hills are fragmented and degraded, with only remnant scattered individuals of <i>A. crustacea </i>and a significantly higher cover of <i>Adenostoma fasciculatum</i>. We still consider such stands as members of the <i>A. crustacea </i>alliance. Additionally, other stands include <i>A. t. </i>ssp. <i>tomentosa </i>as the dominant or co-dominant in the shrub canopy. Since <i>A. crustacea </i>and <i>A. tomentosa </i>overlap ecologically (for example, at Fort Ord Military Reservation), we have some evidence for merging of these two taxa into this one alliance. However, we need more data and analysis to understand relationships between this and other maritime chaparral types. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
