    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast</b> (261Ac-d, Af-h, Aj-k). Stands occur at the Fort Ord Military Reservation, associated with <i>Arctostaphylos pumila, A. tomentosa, Ceanothus cuneatus</i> var. <i>rigidus,</i> and other rare taxa (Griffin 1978, CNPS 2007); on the San Francisco Peninsula in Golden Gate National Recreation Area, associated sometimes with <i>A. montaraensis</i> (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003a); in the Montaña de Oro State Park region on rocky shale, associated with <i>A. morroensis</i> and/or <i>Adenostoma fasciculatum</i> (Holland and Keil 2007); on the UC Santa Cruz campus associating with <i>Arctostaphylos andersonii</i> (UCSC 2006); and in the East Bay Hills sometimes associating with <i>A. pallida</i> and <i>A. auriculata</i> (CNDDB 1993). Stands sampled at Fort Ord (CNPS 2008) indicate that <i>A. crustacea</i> and <i>A. tomentosa</i> occur separately as dominants and together as co-dominants in stands. In San Mateo Co., <i>A. regismontana</i> (CRPR 1B.2) or <i>Quercus parvula </i>occurs as a co-dominant in this alliance (Sikes et al. 2021).</li>
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Ae-f). Stands sampled in the Gabilan Range on granitic soils contain <i>Arctostaphylos crustacea</i> with the rare <i>A. gabilanensis </i>(Matthews 2006, CNPS 2006). Preliminary analysis of 23 plots suggests that <i>A. gabilanensis</i> is an indicator of a locally endemic association of the <i>A. crustacea</i> alliance, and <i>A. crustacea</i> and/or <i>Adenostoma fasciculatum</i> may be a co-dominant in these stands (Bainbridge 2007, Sawyer and Evens 2007). Stands sampled and observed at Fort Ord Military Reservation include <i>Arctostaphylos crustacea</i> as a dominant or codominant in stands.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Coast</b> (261Bc, Bh). Stands occurring on Santa Cruz Island often contain <i>Arctostaphylos insularis</i> (Minnich 1980a). On Santa Rosa Island, most stands contain <i>A. confertiflora</i> (Rodriguez et al. 2017). <i>A. catalinae</i> occurs on Santa Catalina Island (Dixon et al. 2019).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Restrictions and plant adaptations to certain localized edaphic and climatic conditions make this alliance and other maritime chaparral types particularly vulnerable to development and agricultural conversion. Management of maritime chaparral types is problematic because fire history is not well understood. Stands appear to require periodic fire to maintain current species composition, and > 50 years may be adequate to maintain stands. Infrequent fire results in tree encroachment, decline of shrub vigor, and decline in seed bank quality. However, frequent fire tends to convert the stands to coastal scrub or grassland through reducing the chaparral seed bank. </div>
</div>

    

    

    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
